definition.value: A metaphor used to represent an invisible barrier that keeps a given demographic (typically applied to minorities) from rising beyond a certain level in a hierarchy. The metaphor was first coined by feminists in reference to barriers in the careers of high-achieving women.
A metaphor used to describe the combination of individual, cultural, and organizational factors that impede Asian Americans' career progress inside organizations.

A metaphor for the underrepresentation of women in hiring and employment in Hollywood. The term reflects the metaphor of the "glass ceiling," which describes an invisible barrier that keeps a given demographic (typically women, although the term can apply to any protected group) from rising beyond a certain level in a hierarchy.
An informal (and often unacknowledged) barrier to promotion or advancement, in employment and elsewhere, for middle-aged and elderly people.
An informal (and often unacknowledged) barrier to promotion or advancement for younger people, as a result of older people continuing to work instead of retiring.
An informal (and often unacknowledged) barrier to promotion or advancement, in employment and elsewhere, for LGBTQ people.
An unwritten, uncodified barrier to promotion or progression for women in law enforcement or the military.
The assumption that everyone is monosexual (i.e. attracted to only one sex); the belief that bisexuality and pansexuality do not exist.
Discrimination based on one's rank or ranks in given hierarchies.
Abusive, discriminatory, or exploitative behavior towards people because of their rank in a particular hierarchy.
Discrimination based on the language a person uses.
Fear or hatred of Islam or Muslims.
An irrational fear or hatred of Jews.
Fear of or aversion to Hinduism.
A prejudiced attitude about human height that often results in discrimination, based on the belief that unusually short or tall people are inferior and undesirable.
Discrimination based on qualities associated with one's head hair.
A form of discrimination in which persons are targeted based on their hair color.
A form of discrimination in which persons, typically persons with afro-textured hair, are targeted based on their hair texture.
Prejudice or discrimination against people with red hair.
Prejudice based on one's physical appearance.
Fear and dislike of obese people and/or obesity.
Prejudice based on one's gender.
Fear or hatred of cisgender persons.
It is of note that the existence or extent of "cisphobia", like other forms of "reverse" discrimination, is unrecognized by most researchers.
Fear or resentment of heterosexuals or heterosexuality.
It is of note that the existence or extent of "heterophobia", like other forms of "reverse" discrimination, is unrecognized by most researchers.
The notion that one is superior based on one's ability to hear or behave in the manner of one who hears.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual woman.
The sexual functions, activities, attitudes, and orientations of an individual man.
Discrimination against persons with albinism.
Discrimination against persons who have autism.
Prejudice based on one's social class.
A strong antipathy, aversion or hatred toward poverty or poor people.
Prejudice based on one's age.
An irrational fear of adolescent people.
Abnormal and persistent fear of elderly individuals or people; aversion or hatred towards elderly people.
An irrational, obsessive fear or dislike of children.
Discrimination based on religious sect.
Prejudice based on one's diet.
Vegaphobia is an aversion to vegetarian and vegan people.
Discrimination against persons based on their drug usage, either previously or contemporaneously.
An ideological focus on males and men, and issues affecting them, possibly to the detriment of non-males.
An ideological focus on females, and issues affecting them, possibly to the detriment of non-females.
An ideology which expresses perspectives on the way an economy should run and to what end.

An economic ideology is different from an economic theory in that it is normative rather than just explanatory in its approach. An economic theory aims to create accurate explanatory models to describe how an economy currently functions.

An economic ideology is distinct from an economic system (such as a market economy) to the extent that explaining an economic system (positive economics) is distinct from advocating it (normative economics).
Any of various ideologies with primarily social components.
A social ideology focused upon a particular collective or group identity or identities.
The ideology that the phallus, primarily associated with being the male sexual organ (although not all persons with such organs are male), is the central element around which society is organized.
Any of various social ideologies which focus upon gender-specific identities.
Any of various social ideologies which focus upon age-specific identities.
The tendency to customarily view the adult perspective as superior to the youth perspective.
A social ideology which posits that cisgender persons are superior to persons who are not cisgender.
Any of various social ideologies which focus upon ethnicity-specific identities.
